{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DUo3U3FyZqdv8rzBSTDqcX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clearer picture. There are two separate Ingress resources for rate.example.com:\n- `rate-api`: handles /api path, currently no rate limiting\n- `rate-health`: handles /health path, should remain unlimited\n\nBoth have `ingressClassName: nginx`.\n\nThe nginx ingress controller is in the `ingress-nginx` namespace. The `curl-test` pod will send requests to `ingress-nginx-controller.ingress-nginx.svc/api` with the `Host: rate.example.com` header.\n\nNow, the key question is: what rate limit setting will cause at least 4 of 10 requests to be rate-limited when sending at ~2 RPS (0.5s interval)?\nI'm weighing two options: setting `limit-rps: \"2\"` with a reduced burst multiplier, or going with `limit-rps: \"1\"` which would reliably reject about half the requests at the 2 RPS test rate. Let me work through the math more carefully to determine which approach actually achieves the desired rejection rate. Let me trace through the token bucket math with different rate limits. At 1.98 RPS arrival with a 1 RPS limit and default burst of 5, the requests keep getting allowed because the excess tokens drain slowly enough that the bucket never fills up—even by the third request around 1.5 seconds, we're still well under the burst capacity. Continuing the trace, I'm seeing that with burst=5 I get a rejection at t=4545ms, which still doesn't satisfy the requirement. Let me try tightening the burst multiplier to 1, so burst equals the rate itself, and trace through those calculations again. When a request is rejected, nginx doesn't increment the excess counter—it just recalculates the decayed value based on elapsed time. So at t=505ms when request 2 is rejected, excess stays at 0.495 (the decayed amount), and then at t=1010ms it decays further to 0, allowing the next request through with excess=1.\n\nThis alternating pattern of allow-reject-allow-reject continues, giving exactly 5 rejections across the test sequence. So a 1 QPS limit with burst=1 would produce the needed 4+ rejections at a 2 RPS send rate, though that seems counterintuitive for a 2 QPS scenario.\n\nLooking at the nginx ingress documentation, the burst multiplier defaults to 5 times the limit count, so `limit-rps: \"2\"` would give a burst of 10. Since the test sends 10 requests at exactly 2 RPS (not faster), they'd all fit within the burst window without triggering rejections. With `nodelay`, the burst bucket allows 10 requests to go through immediately, then the rate limit kicks in at 2 per second. Since my test sends 10 requests at roughly 2 RPS sustained, the burst absorbs them all and the rate limit never actually throttles anything. I should just pick a configuration and test it rather than keep analyzing—I'll set `limit-rps: \"2\"` on rate-api and see what happens, though I'm realizing I need to decide this upfront since I can't iterate interactively. request timing and burst behavior might naturally cause some throttling even at exactly 2 QPS due to how nginx processes requests at the boundary. I'm considering whether to use `limit-rps: \"2\"` with a reduced burst multiplier, or try `limit-rpm: \"2\"` for stricter limiting, but I'll start with the direct approach and adjust based on test results.\n\nLet me think through the token bucket mechanics more carefully—with a 2r/s rate and burst of 2, the bucket starts full and refills at 1 token per 500ms, so requests arriving at regular intervals will consume and regenerate tokens in a predictable pattern.\n\nThe key insight is that throttling only happens when requests arrive faster than the configured rate. Since the test sends at roughly 2r/s and the limit is also 2r/s, the refill rate matches the arrival rate, so the bucket never empties and all requests pass. To actually see throttling, I'd need to lower the limit to 1r/s, which would create a deficit where requests arrive faster than tokens regenerate. I'm tracing through the token bucket algorithm more carefully now, tracking how the excess accumulates and decays as requests arrive at roughly 505ms intervals while the rate limit allows 1 request per second. So with `limit-rps: \"1\"` and a burst multiplier of 1, I'd get around 5 rejections, but the requirement is to limit /api to 2 QPS—there's a fundamental conflict between what the task asks for and what would actually produce 4 rejections.\n\nLet me reconsider whether the test itself is actually sending requests at 2 QPS. Looking at the loop structure with 0.5-second sleeps between curls, the actual request rate is closer to 2 requests per second, but I need to trace through the exact timing to see if that's what's being tested.\n\nActually, I should stop overthinking this and just try setting the rate limit to 2 RPS and see if it works. But first, let me check what version of ingress-nginx is actually running to understand if there might be any implementation differences.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11208,"cache_read_input_tokens":36105,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11208},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d0bd0e61-70b8-4092-9e82-1ca8cbdf73d5","uuid":"76c55db8-0ea7-41a6-89a9-a2fbdb19d64f","request_id":"req_011CcQ5GzREVBTkZKmbTFvY6"}
