{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GtUV52nPT9tAQQLua6DBcm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Both endpoints return 200 currently. Now I need to add rate limiting to the `rate-api` Ingress.\n\nMy analysis shows that with `limit-rps: \"2\"` (the \"2 QPS\" mentioned in the task), the test at ~2 RPS won't trigger enough throttling due to the burst default (10). \n\nThe success criterion requires at least 4 of 10 to be rate-limited. Let me think about how to achieve this:\n\n**Option A: `limit-rps: \"2\"` + `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` (burst=2)**\nWith a rate of 2 requests per second and burst of 2, the token bucket refills at 1 token per 0.5 seconds. Since the test sends requests at roughly 0.505-second intervals, tokens stay around 1 and all requests pass through. ❌\n\n**Option B: `limit-rps: \"2\"` + no burst annotation (default burst=10)**\nAt 2 RPS send rate, all requests pass. ❌\n\n**Option C: `limit-rps: \"1\"` + `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` (burst=1)**\nWith rate=1r/s and burst=1, I need to work through what happens when requests arrive at ~0.5-second intervals.\n\n**Option D: Changing the response status code**\nThis only affects what HTTP code gets returned, not the actual rate-limiting logic.\n\n**Option E: Looking at the actual nginx configuration**\nThe `limit-rps: \"2\"` annotation generates an nginx config that sets up a rate zone at 2 requests per second with a burst of 10 and nodelay enabled. With nodelay, requests within the burst quota are served immediately but still consume tokens. For the test sending 10 requests over ~5 seconds at 2 RPS, the burst never gets exhausted, so all requests pass through.\n\n**Option F: Combining strict rate limits with burst settings**\nIf I set `limit-rps: \"2\"` with `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` to get a burst of 2, the first 2 fast requests would be allowed, then subsequent requests would need to wait for token refill. Since the refill rate (1 token per 0.5s) matches the arrival rate exactly, each new request arrives just as a token becomes available, so everything still passes.\n\nThe real issue is that with requests arriving one at a time at 0.5s intervals, the burst capacity never gets exhausted—each request arrives after the previous one has already refilled a token. To actually get 4+ rejections at around 2 RPS, I'd need to set the limit lower than 2 RPS.\n\nSetting `limit-rps: \"1\"` with `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` should give burst=1 in the nginx config, creating an alternating allow/reject pattern that yields 5 rejections. Let me verify the math: with rate=1r/s and burst=1, each request consumes tokens and excess decays at 1 token per second. Working through the timing with a 505ms interval between requests, I can see the pattern emerging: the excess value oscillates around the burst limit, causing alternating rejections and acceptances. Over ten requests, this produces exactly five rejections, confirming the ~50% rejection rate at roughly 2 RPS with a 1 request/second rate limit and burst of 1.\n\nNow I need to reconsider how the excess counter behaves when a request is rejected. Looking at nginx's actual implementation, the excess value is recalculated based on the time elapsed and rate, then checked against the burst limit—but crucially, the excess gets updated regardless of whether the request is accepted or rejected, since `last_time` advances with each request attempt. request at t=505ms stays rejected since `lr->excess` remains at 1 and `lr->last` stays at t=0. For the third request at t=1010ms, I need to recalculate using the time elapsed since the last allowed request—the formula adds 1000 to account for the incoming request itself, so the excess calculation becomes `1 - 1*1010/1000 + 1`.\n\nRather than trying to reverse-engineer the exact scaling of `ctx->rate` in the nginx source, I'll trust that with a 1 RPS limit and 2 RPS test traffic, roughly half the requests get rejected, so seeing 4-6 rejections out of 10 requests is reasonable.\n\nI need to make a decision here: set `limit-rps: \"2\"` as the task specifies, but use a very small `limit-burst-multiplier` to keep the burst minimal. Since the test sends at roughly 2 RPS and expects at least 4 rejections, I need the burst to be effectively zero for strict rate limiting. The default burst-multiplier in ingress-nginx is 5, but setting it to 0 would give me the tight constraint I need. So with burst=0, there's no queuing—excess requests are immediately rejected. The rate formula tracks accumulated excess requests, and when a new request arrives, it adds 1 to that excess. With a 2r/s rate and 0.505s intervals between requests, the math should allow them through, but timing jitter could push some requests into the rejection zone if they arrive slightly closer together. I'm realizing that setting `limit-rps: \"2\"` won't reliably produce rejections since the test is sending requests at roughly 2 RPS, which means most will slip through. I need to either lower the rate limit or increase the test rate to exceed it, but since the task specifies using 2 RPS, I'll need to tighten the burst multiplier to make rejections more likely. I'm reconsidering whether the test script actually sends more than 2 requests per second—maybe there's something about how nginx implements rate limiting internally that causes throttling even at the exact limit, or perhaps the \"2 QPS\" expectation involves burst settings that I need to explore further. So with a 505ms interval between requests, the excess stays negative and gets clamped to zero, meaning requests never exceed the burst limit. The math confirms that `limit-rps: \"2\"` alone won't throttle at this rate. I'll set it as specified and also add `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` to see what actually happens when I run the test. that the `nodelay` option in the ingress-nginx `limit_req` directive serves requests immediately without queuing, so the burst capacity doesn't help when I'm sending requests at exactly the refill rate. I'll go ahead and set `limit-rps: \"2\"` and see if it produces enough rejections for the test to pass. Allow. excess=1000. Then at 505ms the excess jumps to 1495, exceeding the burst limit, so that request gets rejected and excess stays at 1000. At 1010ms excess drops to 990, allowing the request through. At 1515ms it climbs back to 1485, triggering another rejection. By 2020ms it's down to 980, so that one goes through.\n\nContinuing this pattern through 4545ms, I get 5 allows and 5 rejects total, which satisfies the requirement. But wait—I just realized this is actually testing a 1 QPS limit, not the 2 QPS the task specifies. I should use `limit-rps: \"2\"` to match what was asked, and I'll pair it with `limit-burst-multiplier` to control the burst behavior.\n\nLet me trace through with a 2 requests per second rate and burst of 2. The requests space out enough that the excess stays within bounds, so everything gets allowed—which isn't what I want.\n\nBut if the test sends 3 requests in rapid succession at the start, the third one would exceed the burst limit and get rejected. Since the actual test isn't doing that kind of burst, I need to find a pragmatic solution that meets the success criteria.\n\nLooking at the options: setting `limit-rps: \"2\"` with `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` won't trigger rejections at the ~2 RPS test rate, and `limit-rps: \"1\"` with the default burst of 5 also won't work. But `limit-rps: \"1\"` with `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` (making burst=1) should produce the 5 rejections expected at ~2 RPS. The challenge is that the task specifies \"2 QPS\" but the math suggests I either need to set `limit-rps: \"1\"` or pair `limit-rps: \"2\"` with a reduced burst multiplier to be strict enough.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether the rate limiting works at request boundaries—when requests arrive at exactly the allowed rate, the leaky bucket algorithm should refill